    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a good start for the students to grasp the core idea. I also want to make sure they understand why some legal scholars criticize this approach, though. They sometimes argue that it's a way for judges to overstep their bounds rather than following the actual text of the Constitution. How should I explain that tension to them so they see why this doctrine is so controversial in legal circles?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To help your students understand the controversy surrounding substantive due process, you could explain that some critics argue that this doctrine relies on an implicit, interpretive vision of constitutional text, rather than strictly adhering to explicit textual language. They contend that judges should not inject personal values or modern interpretations into the Constitution, instead, only the text itself should guide judicial decision-making. This tension between text and interpretation raises concerns about judicial activism and whether judges are merely enforcing the Constitution's \"original intent\" rather than aiming to implement their own, often activist, ideals.",
      "source": "target",
